segments.text: football games and Yale practice, did you all talk about, was there the 12th man, were the traditions then?
Yes.
Did anybody kiss their dates after?
Oh yeah.
That was a wonderful thing back then.
What football games do you remember during that era as being special games?
I don't
I remember any one outstanding one, they were all special, but probably the most special ones was when we had an opportunity to knock Texas off.
And that didn't happen much back then.
Who were the athletic heroes of your student days?
Oh, there was Bob Smith.
I think he came along a little after I...
I think he was in school when I graduated, about the time I graduated.
There was...
Coaches.
I don't even know who was coach then.
I think it was Norton.
Homer Norton?
I think so.
It could have been.
I'm not really sure.
I think he's there at least part of your student days.
Let's see, Muster.
Yeah, we always attended Muster.
Where was that?
We had Muster on campus.
And I don't know how many external musters were going on at that time, but they began to spread pretty rapidly.
And I think it was in Guyon Hall.
Did the veterans participate in muster?
Yeah, they did.
I have the impression that World War II
made muster into something, really, really.
I think it made it to, yeah, I really do.
And I think that's where it really started spreading.
Did you, as an undergraduate, hear anything about the Corregidor muster?
Oh, yeah.
Let's see, final review, no.
Commencement, no.
Silver taps.
Yes, we've stood out in the
Marina there, and then moved to the Corps of the Army area, and built several taps or something, and really got to you.
Particularly, he knew the cadet.
And back then, he knew just about every cadet.
Did you all, on campus, did you all speak to everybody?
Oh, yes.
Yeah, absolutely.
And if you didn't know them, you wouldn't have whipped out.
A bonfire.
Bonfire was different than it is now.
Describe it then.
I mean it wasn't put up engineeringly in the manner it is now.
It was a lot of fun.
He did cut trees.
He did pick up other things to throw in a bonfire too.
I mean it wasn't just any old timbers and things that you could find.
But the significance of it is the same.
Held where?
It was held on for a long time.
It was held on the old red pail.
And who gathered the materials?
Was there anything on top of the bonfire?
Always a crapper.
And where did that come from?
Well, usually back in them days and times, very frankly, we'd steal it.
Did you all have the, were there red pots then?
No, it wasn't that organized then.
And how did you all get things up on the bonfire?
You know, I really don't remember.
Didn't use any kind of a gantry crane or anything?
No, we didn't have one.
We probably blocked the tackles off.
Let's see.
Let's go back to...
to being a fish.
Do you remember any projects you were assigned?
Any tasks that some sophomore gave you?
Describe those.
If you bottled it very much, then that was the case for quite some time.
You're talking about now they're homework assignments?
Yeah.
When it was reading, like in English or, you know, literature and stuff like that.
You'd read it to, or any other assignments you remember?
Projects?
I'm trying to think.
Oh, yeah, we'd always have to go get stuff for them.
You know, things like that.
We later don't have to put.
Mail?
Did you go pick up their mail?
Oh, we picked up everything for them, yeah.
The mail, brought them chow to the dorm when they wanted, whatever they wanted.
Now, could y'all, you couldn't legally carry food out of the dining hall?
No.
Did y'all ever carry food out of the dining hall?
Yeah.
How?
Well, there's lots of ways to do that, but you can do it pretty well.
Describe a room inspection by
Well, when the military wrote an inspection, it was with a white glove.
And the officer doing the inspection would test every place in the room to see if you had dusted and cleaned it well.
Like over the door seals at the top of the doors that come dust there when you just get at it.
Of course, your beds had to be just perfect military.
Your clothes had to be hung just exactly right.
Your socks and shorts were folded just right.
It was a very ethereal inspection.
Other assignments that you remember as a fish?
Were you ever expected to do something that you thought was wrong?
Well, I probably did at the time.
But you don't remember?
But I don't remember.
And as I look back, I wouldn't take anything for a freshman year in the hazing.
I think it ingrained something into a person.
I know they frown on it now, but it didn't hurt me, and I don't think it hurt anybody.
Let's see, we were talking about the students a while ago.
Were there any students of Asian ancestry that you recall?
They weren't in my outfit or any of the neighboring outfits in our dorm, but that's not to say they wasn't.
Hispanic?
They were some Hispanics, yes.
Did y'all have, were they treated any differently?
No.
Did fellow Aggies have nicknames?
Yeah.
What were some of them?
Oh, you know, I mean all kinds of nicknames.
I can't remember them offhand, but Slim or Domino or Rabbit.
It's a lot of things to know to kind of signify characteristics of the individual.
Did you have a nickname?
I may have, but I didn't know it.
Aggie Ring.
Yep.
Do you remember what it cost?
Seemed to me like my Aggie ring was about $35.
Who paid for it?
My dad paid for it.
And was there anything that happened in your heart or feelings when you started wearing that Aggie ring?
You bet.
I mean, that was one of the prouder days of my college career.
And I still have that same ring today, although it's just about totally wore out.
I ordered the new ring about six, seven years ago.
I couldn't make myself take this one off.
Why?
I had just so much sentimentality attached to it, I guess.
What does an Aggie ring mean to you?
Well, you know, there's an old saying, what do you call an Aggie five years after graduation?
Boss.
If you look around the world, and any place you go,
You identify Aggies by their rings, and usually they're in places that are responsible to your leadership.
Share with this machine two or three examples of where an Aggie ring has meant something in your experience.
I guess I probably have met more Aggies on airplanes than anything else that I didn't know.
And I have met them in other parts of the world.
But it seemed like those acquaintances you make on the planes always turned to be beneficial.
But I picked up several clients in my consulting business by having them in Aggie on the plane.
What is Aggie spirit?
It reminds me of a story that
The kid thought that everybody was an Aggie because the dad was.
And he saw a guy with a different type of class ring and it bothered him and he asked his dad and said, dad is that guy an Aggie?
And the guy replied, son, if he's an Aggie he'll tell you proudly.
If he's not, don't be embarrassed.
Aggie spirit is just something that's indwelled in you
It don't take long to get it when you're on that campus.
I've had a lot of people who, since I've, over the years, have told me that they went to A&M, didn't think they were going to stay.
And within six weeks, you couldn't get them away.
It's just that thing that binds them together, binds Aggies together.
Where did that Aggie spirit, where or when did it start with you?
I guess the first week I was on campus.
I was already sold on Aggies.
Did you ever think about leaving?
No.
I was just worried about getting kicked out.
Let's see.
Well, what are the qualities of an Aggie?
The key ingredients.
I think they're gentlemanly, scholarly,
I guess just about every good adjective you can think of tells you what an Aggie is.
All right, the most important question of the whole thing.
We've got two of those.
What did it mean to you?
What has it meant to your life that you went to that institution?
Success.

uh not to saying that i wouldn't have had success otherwise but it put an assurity in me that i knew i had it to do if i just get out and do it and give you that self-confidence to make the moves that you need to make it's just something that when you leave there you know you've got something nobody else has although they may have a college education you've got something that's
even greater than a college education.

You've got that unity of all your students that you go to school with, and any other Aggie you meet, regardless of the classroom, they're going to be willing to help and assist you and aid you in anything.
What feelings do you have in your heart for A&M now?
I guess my big regret is I'm not rich, so I can give a lot of money daily.
I've given a lot of time and service daily, and I've enjoyed every bit of it.
I would do anything they asked me to do.
And if I ever hit that jackpot, they're going to get the most out of it.
